results.notes: This mushroom is relatively small with a greyish tan to darker cream colored pileus. The pileus and stipe are extremely slippery when wet. The pileus is conic to convex, smooth, slightly sticky, with almost translucent striate margin. The pileus is about 2-4cm in diameter. The stipe is whitish to darker cream colored, skinny, hollow, equal, extremely fragile, smooth, and 2-5 cm in length. The base of the stipe is rhizomorph. The stipe is also central and slightly curved to straight. SPORE PRINT: Not produced. Spores are light colored and largely cylindrical ranging from 7-10 (um) by 4-5 (um). Spores appear to not be amyloid

results.notes:
Two, on a large, mossy, mostly decorticate pine log.
I had earlier confused this with the Hypholoma of 535622 based mostly on physical proximity.
A revisit on 11/13 showed the larger essentially unchanged, with the cap margin still close to the substrate (and I believe I had collected the smaller one on 11/8 but then lost it).
I’m not quite sure if the fine white hairs are mostly confined to the margin or only more visible there. They seem present throughout the cap.
I collected the larger one and it gave no visible spore print, but tellingly, the white gills dried pale yellowish, not darker purplish as in the Hypholoma.
Cap separated readily (though not cleanly) from the stem on collection. I’m not sure, but the gills seem to have been attached.
Dried stem tasted mild.
As I failed to photograph the fresh gills and stem, I add a photo of the dried specimen. The cap is still almost a cm across. The gills appear somewhat distant and thin, the stem ridged.
